### KV Namespace Management with MCP Tools

Source: https://context7.com/cloudflare/mcp-server-cloudflare/llms.txt

Register and utilize KV (Key-Value) namespace management tools within an MCP agent. This enables clients to list, create, update, and delete KV namespaces programmatically. It requires importing the necessary tools and registering them during agent initialization.

```typescript
// Register KV tools in your MCP agent
import { registerKVTools } from '@repo/mcp-common/src/tools/kv_namespace.tools'

export class WorkersBindingsMCP extends McpAgent<Env, WorkersBindingsMCPState, Props> {
  async init() {
    this.server = new CloudflareMCPServer({
      userId,
      wae: this.env.MCP_METRICS,
      serverInfo: {
        name: this.env.MCP_SERVER_NAME,
        version: this.env.MCP_SERVER_VERSION,
      },
    })

    registerAccountTools(this)
    registerKVTools(this)
    registerWorkersTools(this)
    registerR2BucketTools(this)
    registerD1Tools(this)
    registerHyperdriveTools(this)
  }
}

// Example tool call from client:
// "List my KV namespaces"
// Returns: { namespaces: [{ id: "abc123", title: "my-kv-store" }], count: 1 }

// "Create a new KV namespace called 'session-cache'"
// Returns: { id: "xyz789", title: "session-cache", supports_url_encoding: true }
```

--------------------------------

### Custom Tool Registration for Cloudflare KV Namespace Creation (TypeScript)

Source: https://context7.com/cloudflare/mcp-server-cloudflare/llms.txt

Registers a custom tool named 'kv_namespace_create' to create new KV namespaces in a Cloudflare account. It includes validation schemas and metadata, handles account ID retrieval, and uses the Cloudflare client to perform the creation. Error handling is included for the creation process.

```typescript
agent.server.tool(
  'kv_namespace_create',
  'Create a new kv namespace in your Cloudflare account',
  {
    title: KvNamespaceTitleSchema,
  },
  {
    title: 'Create KV namespace',
    annotations: {
      readOnlyHint: false,
      destructiveHint: false,
    },
  },
  async ({ title }) => {
    const account_id = await agent.getActiveAccountId()
    if (!account_id) {
      return MISSING_ACCOUNT_ID_RESPONSE
    }
    try {
      const props = getProps(agent)
      const client = getCloudflareClient(props.accessToken)
      const namespace = await client.kv.namespaces.create({ account_id, title })
      return {
        content: [
          {
            type: 'text',
            text: JSON.stringify(namespace),
          },
        ],
      }
    } catch (error) {
      return {
        content: [
          {
            type: 'text',
            text: `Error creating KV namespace: ${error instanceof Error ? error.message : String(error)}`,
          },
        ],
      }
    }
  }
)

```

### Cloudflare DNS Analytics MCP Server

Source: https://github.com/cloudflare/mcp-server-cloudflare/blob/main/apps/dns-analytics/README.md

This MCP server integrates tools powered by the [Cloudflare DNS Analytics API](https://developers.cloudflare.com/api/resources/dns/) to provide insights on DNS analytics and optimization. The currently available tools include listing zones, fetching DNS reports, and retrieving DNS settings for accounts and zones.

--------------------------------

### Cloudflare MCP Server > APIs and Functions > KV Namespace Management

Source: https://context7.com/cloudflare/mcp-server-cloudflare/llms.txt

Manage KV namespaces in your Cloudflare account directly through MCP tools. You can list existing namespaces, create new ones with specified names, update their configurations, and delete them as needed. This is achieved by registering and utilizing the KV tools within your MCP agent, enabling client requests like 'List my KV namespaces' or 'Create a new KV namespace called `session-cache`'.

--------------------------------

### Cloudflare MCP Server > DNS Analytics server

Source: https://github.com/cloudflare/mcp-server-cloudflare/blob/main/README.md

The DNS Analytics server assists in optimizing DNS performance and debugging related issues. Users can analyze their current DNS setup and identify areas for improvement or potential problems.

